%I A087280 #36 Jul 01 2026 16:49:42
%S A087280 5,8,10,12,24
%N A087280 Solutions n of max(m+d(m))=n+2 for m<n; d(m) is the number of divisors of m.
%C A087280 It is not known if there are other terms. There are no more terms < 10^10.
%C A087280 There are no more terms <= 10^12. - _Patrik Idén_, Jun 13 2026
%D A087280 R. K. Guy, Unsolved Problems in Number Theory, section B8.
%H A087280 Paul Erdős, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2689842">Some Unconventional Problems in Number Theory</a>, Mathematics Magazine, Vol. 52, No. 2, Mar., 1979, pp. 67-70. See Problem 4. p. 68.
%H A087280 Patrik Idén, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21084248">Computational Verification of Erdős Problem 647 up to 10^12: Gap-Growth Analysis and Depth-Record Extension</a>, Zenodo preprint v2, 2026.
%e A087280 The largest value of m+d(m) for m < n=8 is 6+d(6)=10 = n+2, so 8 is in the sequence.
%K A087280 nonn,more,changed
%O A087280 1,1
%A A087280 _Jud McCranie_, Aug 28 2003
